# Motivation

A protocol family that spans transport, message objects, replay semantics,
work-claims, checkpointing, scripting, package deployment, archival retrieval,
and Bitcoin anchoring cannot remain coherent if each document uses different
words for the same concepts or the same word for different concepts.

Existing Bitcoin proposals benefit from precise naming and narrow scope. Kapnet
requires the same discipline. This document provides that common vocabulary so
that later BIPs do not repeatedly redefine basic objects and do not silently
drift in meaning over time.

# Specification

## Conformance Language

The key words "MUST", "MUST NOT", "REQUIRED", "SHALL", "SHALL NOT", "SHOULD",
"SHOULD NOT", "RECOMMENDED", "NOT RECOMMENDED", "MAY", and "OPTIONAL" in this
document are to be interpreted as described in BCP 14 when, and only when, they
appear in all capitals.

## Scope

This document defines:

- terminology,
- notation,
- naming conventions,
- identifier formatting guidance,
- hash and encoding notation,
- time and ordering vocabulary,
- distinctions between replay-critical and policy-local behavior.

This document does not by itself define any new byte format, consensus rule,
relay policy, or execution semantics.

## General Terminology

### Kapnet

Kapnet is the protocol family described by this repository. It is an overlay
protocol system that may interact with Bitcoin as a settlement or anchoring
substrate while maintaining its own message, replay, execution, and state
structures unless explicitly defined otherwise.

### Overlay

An overlay is any protocol behavior, data structure, message format, ordering
rule, or execution rule that is external to Bitcoin consensus validity unless a
separate Bitcoin proposal explicitly says otherwise.

### Replay Domain

A replay domain is the set of conditions under which a message or state
transition is considered to belong to one shared causally-evaluated history.

Replay domains are usually determined by a combination of network id,
namespace, state root lineage, and message identity rules.

### Namespace

A namespace is a scoped region of Kapnet meaning or state. Namespaces may refer
to DAOs, guilds, rooms, package domains, market domains, archival domains, or
other application-level partitions.

A namespace identifier MUST be treated as an opaque identifier unless a more
specific BIP defines its internal derivation.

### Object

An object is any canonically serialized Kapnet byte sequence with a type and
version. Objects may be top-level or nested.

### Identifier

An identifier is a stable reference to an object, namespace, key, market slot,
state leaf, or other protocol entity.

Unless otherwise stated, identifiers are byte strings rather than human-readable
names.

## Messaging Terminology

### TXXM

TXXM, or Transaction CrossMail, is the top-level Kapnet message envelope. A TXXM
commits to payload data, dependencies, sender identity, validity bounds, and
other generic relay and replay properties.

### Payload

A payload is the semantic body committed by a TXXM envelope. The payload defines
the application-level meaning of the message.

### Message Class

A message class is the registered semantic family of a TXXM payload, such as
submission, validation, vote, governance action, market object, or receipt.

### Attachment

An attachment is external or auxiliary content committed to by a message but not
necessarily embedded inline in the replay-critical body.

### Blob

A blob is a large content-addressed attachment or chunked content object whose
retrieval and retention may be handled separately from live relay.

## Ordering Terminology

### Braid

A braid is the live concurrent ordering surface formed by accepted Kapnet
message objects prior to checkpoint crystallization.

A braid preserves concurrency, partial ordering, and conflict structure.

### Braid Node

A braid node is a specific live ordering unit corresponding to one accepted
message and its associated weight, dependencies, and conflict keys.

### Frontier

The frontier is the current set of live braid tips not yet strictly dominated by
heavier or later-compatible descendants.

### Conflict Key

A conflict key is an identifier representing an exclusivity class. Two nodes
sharing a conflict key may be mutually exclusive if the consuming rules so
state.

### Candidate Braid

A candidate braid is a compatible down-closed subset of live braid nodes under
consideration for checkpoint inclusion.

### Knot

A knot is a crystallized checkpoint object derived from a selected candidate
braid and a deterministic replay procedure.

### Checkpoint

A checkpoint is the act or result of reducing the live braid into an ordered,
durable state transition with a committed post-state root.

### Finalization

Finalization is the condition under which a knot is no longer subject to valid
replacement within a given replay domain.

## State Terminology

### State Root

A state root is the cryptographic commitment to the full persistent Kapnet state
at a particular replay boundary.

### Subroot

A subroot is a top-level or nested subtree commitment within the larger state
commitment tree.

### Leaf

A leaf is a committed key-value entry in the state structure.

### Inclusion Proof

An inclusion proof is a proof that a given leaf or object is committed under a
particular root.

### Non-Inclusion Proof

A non-inclusion proof is a proof that no committed leaf exists at a queried key
under a particular root.

### Atomic Replay Step

An atomic replay step is the full state mutation produced by one successfully
replayed message or execution result, applied as an indivisible unit.

## Work Terminology

### Weakwork

Weakwork is a protocol-defined proof object representing scarce computational
effort below Bitcoin’s full proof-of-work threshold and usable for local Kapnet
ordering, admission, or market functions.

### Weakwork Claim

A weakwork claim is the canonically serialized object asserting that a claimant
has produced valid weakwork for a specific domain, challenge, and target.

### Claim Domain

The claim domain is the explicit domain separator that prevents the unintended
reuse of a weakwork claim across unrelated contexts.

### Work Digest

The work digest is the proof result checked against a threshold according to the
weakwork validation rules.

### Heavy Auxiliary Proof of Work

Heavy auxiliary proof of work, or heavy auxPoW, is a proof or commitment system
intended to connect Kapnet claims to stronger external proof contexts such as
Bitcoin block production. Its exact meaning is defined by separate BIPs.

### Hashproductive Capital

Hashproductive capital refers to resources controlled for the purpose of
producing work-like proofs, including but not limited to weakwork or auxiliary
proofs.

## Execution Terminology

### KScript

KScript is the Kapnet virtual machine language and execution model for bounded,
deterministic programmable behavior.

### Program

A program is a canonically encoded KScript bytecode object.

### Execution Result

An execution result is the deterministic outcome of running a KScript program,
including success or failure status, return values, and state-write intent.

### Write Intent

A write intent is a structured statement of proposed state mutation produced by
execution but not applied until accepted by the surrounding replay logic.

### Host Interface

The host interface is the standardized boundary between KScript execution and
externally provided state, permissions, or services.

### Kapplet

A kapplet is a packaged Kapnet execution module containing code, manifest
metadata, dependency declarations, and lifecycle policy.

## Governance and Social Terminology

### DAO

A DAO is a first-class Kapnet governance object with manifest, treasury,
capability, and rule surfaces defined by separate BIPs.

### Guild

A guild is a higher-level namespace grouping or institutional domain used for
organization and discourse.

### Room

A room is a scoped discourse or coordination subspace, generally contained
within a guild or other parent namespace.

### Submission

A submission is a user- or agent-originated content object or action object that
serves as a primary unit of discourse or coordination.

### Validation

Validation is the act of attesting to, scoring, checking, or otherwise evaluating
a submission or other protocol object according to defined rules.

### Membership Proof

A membership proof is an object attesting that an identity or capability holds
standing within a namespace or institution.

### Reputation Object

A reputation object is a portable or local state object representing standing,
history, score, or privilege in a context defined by separate BIPs.

## Relay and Archival Terminology

### Relay

A relay is a service that forwards, admits, stores, or refuses Kapnet objects
according to protocol rules and local policy.

### Admission Control

Admission control is the set of rules determining whether an object is accepted
for transport, storage, or replay consideration.

### Postage

Postage is the pricing or burn-like surface associated with resource consumption
such as routing, storage, retrieval, or priority handling.

### Hedlbit

Hedlbit is the protocol unit used by certain Kapnet documents for postage,
reserve-time accounting, or resource pricing.

### Provider

A provider is a service that offers content retrieval, archival retention,
lookup, or other support functions.

### Retrieval Proof

A retrieval proof is evidence that a requested object, attachment, or blob was
delivered or is authentically unavailable.

## Bitcoin Interface Terminology

### Anchor

An anchor is a Bitcoin-facing or externally published commitment to a Kapnet
object, root, batch, or proof identifier.

### Anchoring

Anchoring is the act of encoding or publishing a Kapnet commitment into a
Bitcoin-relevant carrier or equivalent external substrate.

### Carrier Surface

A carrier surface is the location or mechanism through which an anchor payload
is published, such as an OP_RETURN output, coinbase-carried payload, or other
approved structure.

### Settlement Hook

A settlement hook is a standardized interface point by which Kapnet objects or
summaries may reference or interact with Bitcoin transaction-level publication.

### Overlay-Valid

Overlay-valid means valid according to Kapnet rules without implying anything
about Bitcoin relay, mining, standardness, or consensus acceptance.

### Policy-Compatible

Policy-compatible means plausibly admissible under prevailing software or miner
behavior, but not guaranteed by consensus.

## Notation

### Byte Strings

Byte strings are written as hexadecimal when displayed textually, without
embedded whitespace unless formatting requires grouping.

Unless otherwise stated, hexadecimal is case-insensitive.

### Hashes

`H(x)` denotes a cryptographic hash of `x` as defined by the consuming BIP.

`H2(x)` denotes double application of the hash function when that convention is
used.

A displayed hash value is a byte string, not an integer, unless explicitly
stated otherwise.

### Concatenation

`x || y` denotes bytewise concatenation.

### Ordering

“Lexicographic order” means bytewise lexicographic order over canonical encoded
bytes unless another order is explicitly named.

### Integer Interpretation

When a hash digest or byte string is interpreted as an integer, it MUST be
interpreted as a non-negative big-endian integer unless another BIP explicitly
states otherwise.

### Time

Unix timestamps are seconds since the Unix epoch in UTC unless otherwise stated.

“Freshness” refers to admissibility relative to a bounded time interval, not to
subjective recency.

### Height and Index

“Height” refers to a sequence position in a chain-like or checkpoint-like
history.

“Index” refers to a position in a list, registry, or checkpoint sequence.

## Naming Conventions

BIPs in this repository SHOULD use the following naming patterns where relevant:

- `*_id` for opaque stable identifiers
- `*_hash` for a cryptographic hash of canonical bytes
- `*_root` for a Merkle, sparse Merkle, or similar commitment root
- `*_count` for explicit cardinality
- `*_flags` for bitfields
- `created_at`, `valid_from`, `valid_until`, `expires_at` for timestamps
- `network_id`, `namespace_id`, `checkpoint_index` for scoped identifiers

These are conventions, not by themselves consensus rules, unless a later BIP
makes a specific field normative.

## Replay-Critical Versus Policy-Local Behavior

A rule is replay-critical if violating or interpreting it differently can lead to
different canonical object identities, different candidate selection, different
replay results, or different committed state roots.

A rule is policy-local if it affects admission, storage, preference, pricing, or
display behavior without altering replay-critical outcomes.

Specifications SHOULD clearly distinguish these categories.

## Undefined Terms

If a later BIP introduces a new term not defined here, that BIP SHOULD define it
explicitly and SHOULD do so in a way that does not conflict with this glossary.

# Rationale

Kapnet needs an explicit distinction between transport, replay, execution,
policy, and anchoring vocabulary. Without that separation, terms like “valid,”
“accepted,” “included,” “anchored,” and “finalized” become dangerously
overloaded.

This document also formalizes the distinction between overlay validity and
Bitcoin compatibility so that Bitcoin-facing documents do not overclaim what the
base chain recognizes.

# Backward Compatibility

This document is informational only. It introduces no wire-format changes,
consensus rules, or policy requirements for Bitcoin or Kapnet implementations.

# Security Considerations

Terminology drift is not merely editorial. Ambiguous words can cause real
implementation divergence, especially around replay boundaries, proof reuse,
state mutation, and anchoring claims.

Authors of later BIPs SHOULD avoid synonyms that blur the distinction between:

- valid and accepted,
- accepted and included,
- included and finalized,
- anchored and verified,
- policy-compatible and consensus-enforced.

